Topic: Exception Handling (Very Important)

üìÖ Date: 06 February 2026
‚è±Ô∏è Duration: ~45 minutes

1Ô∏è‚É£ What is an Exception?

An exception is an error that occurs during program execution.

Example:

print(10 / 0)

‚ùå Error:

ZeroDivisionError

If we don‚Äôt handle it ‚Üí program crashes.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Basic try‚Äìexcept
try:
    num = int(input("Enter number: "))
    print(10 / num)
except:
    print("Something went wrong")

Now program won‚Äôt crash.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Catch Specific Errors (Best Practice üî•)
try:
    num = int(input("Enter number: "))
    print(10 / num)

except ZeroDivisionError:
    print("Cannot divide by zero")

except ValueError:
    print("Invalid input")
4Ô∏è‚É£ Using else

else runs if no error occurs.

try:
    num = int(input("Enter number: "))
    result = 10 / num

except ZeroDivisionError:
    print("Cannot divide by zero")

else:
    print("Result is", result)
5Ô∏è‚É£ finally Block

finally always runs.

try:
    print("Try block")
except:
    print("Error")
finally:
    print("Always runs")
6Ô∏è‚É£ Raising Custom Exception
age = int(input("Enter age: "))

if age < 18:
    raise Exception("Not eligible")
üî• Why Exception Handling is Important?

Prevents program crash

Makes code professional

Required in real applications

Very important in projects

üß† Memory Trick

try ‚Üí risky code

except ‚Üí handle error

else ‚Üí no error

finally ‚Üí always run
